               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470614-name-958" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-958" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-958" type="surname" value="CROUCHER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-958" type="given" value="ELIJAH"></interp>ELIJAH CROUCHER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a baker, and live in High-street, St. Giles's.—the prisoner has been in my employ. On the 14th of June, between eight and nine o'clock in the evening, he went out—I followed, overtook him, and</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184706140167"></xptr>
               <p>charged him with having some flour—he admitted that he had it—he did not say how he came by it—I gave him charge—it is my property, and was in my bag, with my name on it—it is the sort of flour I had on my premises—he said if I would forgive him, he would not do it again.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> You never followed me, you met me. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> I followed you—I did not go round Craven-street at all.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470614-name-959" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-959" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-959" type="surname" value="BASK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-959" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH BASK</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Police-constable F.</hi> 124.) On the night of the 14th of June. the prisoner was given into my charge, by Croucher—I searched him, and found in each pocket a paper bag of flour, and a night-cap half full of flour, between his waistcoat and coat, which was buttoned up—I took him to the station—he said it was the first time, and he hoped his master would forgive him.</p>
